snippet: The Parliament first said it would be at least five weeks before members would even try to elect a speaker, then said that members would try to meet Sunday — only five days later than originally planned.
abstract: Iraqi Parliament says it will be at least five weeks before members will even try to elect speaker, first step in process of forming government; plan receives firestorm of criticism from friendly countries and Shiite clerics and Parliament members say they will try to meet sooner.

byline.original: By ALISSA J. RUBIN and SUADAD AL-SALHY
byline.contributor: An employee of The New York Times contributed reporting from Anbar Province, Iraq.

lead_paragraph: The Parliament first said it would be at least five weeks before members would even try to elect a speaker, then said that members would try to meet Sunday — only five days later than originally planned.

headline.main: Iraqi Parliament Wobbles Over Forming Government
headline.print_headline: Iraqi Parliament Wobbles Over Forming Government
